<h2 align="center" style="color: rgb(51, 51, 255);"><big> Component Types -- Enterprise Beans<br>
</big></h2>
<big><big><big>Two types of Enterprise Beans:</big></big></big>
<ul>
  <li><big><big><font color="#ff0000">Session
Beans:&nbsp;</font> </big></big></li>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p style="margin-top: 6px; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><big><big>Can
update data in a database and participate in
transactions.</big></big> </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p style="margin-top: 6px; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><big><big>Either
Stateful or Stateless.</big></big> </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</ul>
<ul>
    <li><big><big><font color="#ff0000">Entity
        Beans:&nbsp;</font> </big></big></li>
    <ul>
    <li>
      <p style="margin-top: 6px; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><big><big>Most
complex component type in EJB model.</big></big> </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p style="margin-top: 6px; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><big><big>Operate
as business objects and represent data in a
database or a persistent data storage.
      </big></big> </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</ul>
      <p style="margin-top: 6px; margin-bottom: 0pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </p>
<ul>
    <li>
      <p style="margin-top: 6" align="justify">
<big><big>Each provides its own type of functionality and can enable
the container to manage that functionality or manage by itself.</big></big></li>
    <li>
      <p style="margin-top: 6" align="justify">
<big><big>
Beans that manage their own functionality are more complex but also
have more options.</big></big></li>
    <li>
      <p style="margin-top: 6" align="justify"><big><big>Session beans and
      entity beans use synchronous communication.</big></big></li>
    <li>
      <p style="margin-top: 6" align="justify"><big><big>EJB executes client
      requests and client waits for the EJB response.</big></big><br>
    </li>
</ul>
